        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Local ranking factors</strong> are the signals Google evaluates to determine business placement in the local pack, Google Maps, and local organic results. Google publicly confirms three primary categories: relevance, distance, and prominence. Moz and Whitespark research identifies eight signal groups — GBP signals alone account for roughly 36% of local pack rankings, making your Google Business Profile the highest-leverage single asset in local SEO.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Top signal group</div>
            <div class="tms-value">GBP signals (~36%)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Review signals</div>
            <div class="tms-value">~17% of rankings</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Most local SEO efforts fail not because the tactics are wrong, but because they're investing in the wrong factors. A business building 200 directory citations while ignoring their primary GBP category is optimising a 7% signal while neglecting a 36% signal. Understanding factor weights changes where you spend your time.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What are local ranking factors?</h2>
        <p>Local ranking factors are the specific signals that determine where a business appears in Google's location-based search results — the local pack (the map with 3 business listings), Google Maps, and local organic results (blue links below the pack).</p>
        <p>Google has publicly confirmed three primary factors at a high level: relevance, distance, and prominence. Industry researchers at Moz and Whitespark run annual surveys of local SEO practitioners and correlation studies to estimate the weights of individual signals within those categories. The consensus weighting from Moz's research:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>GBP signals: ~36%</strong> of local pack rankings</li>
          <li><strong>Review signals: ~17%</strong></li>
          <li><strong>On-page signals: ~16%</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Link signals: ~11%</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Citation signals: ~7%</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Behavioral signals: ~7%</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Personalization: ~6%</strong></li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Google's public confirmation</div>
          <p>Google's official guidance states: "Local results are based primarily on relevance, distance, and prominence." The company explains that businesses can influence relevance through their Business Profile, distance through their address/service area, and prominence through reviews, citations, and their website's authority. Source: Google Business Profile Help.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why understanding local ranking factors matters</h2>
        <p>The local pack shows only 3 businesses per search. Understanding factor weights gives you a competitive edge in four ways:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Prioritization saves resources.</strong> If you understand that GBP signals carry 36% of the ranking weight and citation signals carry 7%, you know to spend the first 10 hours on GBP completeness — not on building your 200th directory citation.</li>
          <li><strong>Different algorithm from organic.</strong> A business ranking #1 organically may not appear in the local pack at all. The signals that drive organic rankings and local pack rankings overlap but are weighted differently. What works for one doesn't automatically work for the other.</li>
          <li><strong>Limited slots amplify precision.</strong> Only 3 businesses appear in the local pack per query. In a market with 50 local businesses, marginal optimization gains translate directly into competitive wins or losses.</li>
          <li><strong>Competitive intelligence.</strong> Knowing which factors matter most lets you audit competitor profiles and identify their weaknesses. A competitor with 300 reviews but no GBP posts and wrong primary category is beatable through targeted improvements.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How each local ranking factor category works</h2>

        <h3>1. GBP signals (~36%)</h3>
        <p>Your Google Business Profile is the largest factor group. Every field matters, but some matter more than others:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Primary category</strong> — the single highest-impact individual factor. "Dentist" vs "Healthcare Provider" determines whether you appear for dental queries at all. Audit yours against what your best-ranked competitors use.</li>
          <li>Secondary categories, services listed, attributes</li>
          <li>Business name keyword relevance</li>
          <li>Profile completeness score</li>
          <li>GBP posts activity and Q&A engagement</li>
          <li>GBP photos volume and recency</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>2. Review signals (~17%)</h3>
        <p>Google Reviews impact rankings through six distinct dimensions:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Total review count</li>
          <li>Average star rating</li>
          <li>Review velocity — new reviews per month (recency weighted heavily)</li>
          <li>Review recency — how recent are the latest reviews</li>
          <li>Keywords in review text</li>
          <li>Owner response rate and response time</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The velocity vs volume distinction matters: a business with 200 reviews that's received none in 6 months can lose rankings to a competitor with 85 reviews who gets 8-10 new ones monthly. Google's algorithm treats recent review activity as a freshness and activity signal.</p>

        <h3>3. On-page signals (~16%)</h3>
        <p>Your website's content feeds into local pack rankings through the prominence signal. Key on-page factors:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>NAP (Name, Address, Phone) appearing consistently on the website</li>
          <li>City and state name in title tags and H1s on location pages</li>
          <li>Local content on service pages</li>
          <li>LocalBusiness schema markup</li>
          <li>Domain authority (underlying page authority)</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>4. Link signals (~11%)</h3>
        <p>Backlinks contribute to local pack rankings through the prominence factor. Local links from community organizations, local newspapers, and industry directories carry more weight than generic national links. See: <a href="/glossary/local-link-building/">local link building</a>.</p>

        <h3>5. Citation signals (~7%)</h3>
        <p>Citation volume, NAP consistency across directories, and citation quality all contribute. Getting listed on the major directories with perfectly consistent information is foundational. Inconsistencies between your GBP, website, and directory listings create data confusion that suppresses local relevance scoring.</p>

        <h3>6. Behavioral signals (~7%)</h3>
        <p>Google tracks how users interact with your listing: click-through rate from search results, mobile clicks-to-call, direction requests, and time spent on your website. These are harder to directly optimize but improve naturally when your profile is complete and your reviews are strong.</p>

        <h3>7. Personalization (~6%)</h3>
        <p>The searcher's location, search history, and device type all influence which results they see. Proximity is entirely based on the searcher's GPS or IP location — this component cannot be optimized.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Google's three primary factor categories</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
