        <h2 id="examples">Real local ranking factor examples</h2>

        <h3>Example 1 — Wrong primary category costs a dentist 6 months</h3>
        <p>A Portland dentist with 100+ reviews and a 4.8 rating couldn't break into the local pack. Audit revealed their primary GBP category was "Dental Clinic" — a category patients don't search for. After switching to "Dentist" (the most commonly searched category for dental practices), they appeared in the local pack within 3 weeks. The primary category carries so much weight that a single change produced results faster than 6 months of citation building had.</p>

        <h3>Example 2 — Review velocity beats review volume</h3>
        <p>A Chicago plumber with 85 Google Reviews ranked below competitors with 150-200 reviews. But those competitors had received no new reviews in four months. The plumber implemented a systematic post-service text message campaign — "Did we solve your problem? Leave us a quick review" — generating 10-15 new reviews monthly. Within 60 days, they moved to position #1. Review velocity (8+ per month) beat static volume (150 with none recent). The recency weighting in Google's review signal is more powerful than most businesses realise.</p>

        <h3>Example 3 — Law firm builds prominence through content</h3>
        <p>A Dallas personal injury law firm with solid GBP optimization but weak online prominence was stuck at position #4. They began publishing two blog posts monthly targeting local queries — "car accident lawyer Dallas," "Texas personal injury statute of limitations" — and combined this with steady review acquisition. Over 6 months, their website's domain authority grew, local links from citations and community work accumulated, and they moved to position #2. Prominence takes the longest to build but compounds indefinitely.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Local ranking factors vs organic ranking factors</h2>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Local ranking factors (unique to local)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Google Business Profile is the #1 signal group</li>
              <li>Physical proximity to searcher (distance factor)</li>
              <li>Google Reviews as a direct, major ranking signal</li>
              <li>Citation NAP consistency across directories</li>
              <li>Behavioral signals: calls, directions, clicks from pack</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Organic ranking factors (different from local)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Website content and E-E-A-T signals primary</li>
              <li>No proximity component at all</li>
              <li>Reviews are indirect (trust signals, CTR)</li>
              <li>Citations have minimal direct impact</li>
              <li>Behavioral: dwell time, bounce rate, CTR from organic</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for optimizing local ranking factors</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Fix your primary GBP category first.</strong> It's the single highest-impact individual factor. Check it against your top-ranked local competitors and use the most specific category that matches how customers search for you.</li>
          <li><strong>Build review velocity, not just volume.</strong> Set up a systematic review request process — a post-service email or text. 5-10 new reviews monthly beats a one-time campaign to get 50 that then stops completely.</li>
          <li><strong>Audit NAP inconsistencies before building new citations.</strong> Adding more citations with inconsistent data makes the problem worse. Find and fix all discrepancies first, then build on a clean data foundation.</li>
          <li><strong>Complete every GBP field.</strong> Services, attributes, hours, description, photos, Q&A. Incomplete profiles signal to Google that the business may be inactive or unreliable. Profile completeness correlates strongly with local pack position.</li>
          <li><strong>Post to GBP weekly.</strong> Activity signals freshness. A business that posted last month ranks below a business that posts weekly, all other factors being equal. The posts themselves drive small direct traffic but the ranking signal from activity consistency is the primary benefit.</li>
          <li><strong>Publish local content monthly.</strong> Blog posts targeting "[service] in [city]" keywords strengthen both on-page signals and the prominence factor. 2-4 posts monthly build compounding authority that feeds into local pack rankings over 6-12 months.</li>
          <li><strong>Track factor movement, not just rankings.</strong> Ranking changes lag factor improvements by 4-8 weeks. Monitor GBP insights (calls, directions, views), review velocity, and citation consistency as leading indicators rather than waiting solely for ranking movements.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — optimising the wrong factors</div>
          <p>The most common local SEO mistake is spending the majority of the budget on citation building (7% of the ranking signal) while neglecting GBP optimization (36%) and review velocity (17%). Do the math: 10 hours on citation building vs 10 hours on GBP completeness, category optimization, and setting up a review request system will produce dramatically different results. Fix the highest-weight signals first.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common local ranking factor mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Wrong primary GBP category</strong> — the most fixable, highest-impact mistake. Audit yours today against what top-ranked competitors in your market use.</li>
          <li><strong>Review velocity dropping to zero</strong> — even businesses with 300+ reviews can lose local pack positions if they stop getting new reviews. Velocity is weighted heavily in Google's review signal.</li>
          <li><strong>NAP inconsistencies across citations</strong> — your phone number formatted as (512) 555-1234 in one place and 5125551234 in another creates data confusion. Standardize across all listings.</li>
          <li><strong>No photos or outdated photos</strong> — Google's algorithm can assess photo recency. Listings with photos added in the last 30 days outperform those with photos from 2019.</li>
          <li><strong>Building citations before fixing inconsistencies</strong> — amplifies the problem instead of solving it. Audit first, fix inconsistencies, then build.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring behavioral signals</strong> — low click-through rates from search results and low call conversion rates from the pack depress rankings over time. Improve your GBP photos, primary category match, and review display to increase CTR.</li>
        </ul>

